  "pa.freud.libraryTitle": "Freud library",
  "pa.freud.libraryDesc": "Reference material on Freud's life, concepts and major works.",
  "pa.freud.err.notConfigured": "AI is not configured on the server. Contact support.",
  "pa.freud.err.failed": "Could not get a response. Try again.",
  "pa.freud.err.rateLimited": "You have reached the hourly question limit. Please try again later.",
  "pa.freud.suggest.1": "What is transference?",
  "pa.freud.suggest.2": "Explain the Oedipus complex",
  "pa.freud.suggest.3": "How does dream interpretation work?",
  "pa.freud.suggest.4": "What are defense mechanisms?",
  "pa.freud.section.biography": "Biography",
  "pa.freud.section.biographyIntro": "Sigmund Freud (1856–1939), Austrian neurologist and founder of psychoanalysis.",
  "pa.freud.bio.early": "Early years and medical training",
  "pa.freud.bio.earlyBody": "Born in Freiberg, Moravia, Freud studied medicine in Vienna. Early work with Charcot in Paris and Breuer in Vienna on hysteria led to the discovery of the talking cure and the role of unconscious processes.",
  "pa.freud.bio.vienna": "Vienna and the birth of psychoanalysis",
  "pa.freud.bio.viennaBody": "From the 1890s, Freud developed free association, dream interpretation and the theory of the unconscious. The Interpretation of Dreams (1900) marks the founding moment of psychoanalysis as a discipline.",
  "pa.freud.bio.movement": "The psychoanalytic movement",
  "pa.freud.bio.movementBody": "Freud gathered collaborators (Jung, Adler, Ferenczi, among others), founded the International Psychoanalytical Association (1910) and faced theoretical splits. The movement spread across Europe and the Americas.",
  "pa.freud.bio.late": "Late work and exile",
  "pa.freud.bio.lateBody": "After the structural model (id, ego, superego), Freud fled Nazi Austria in 1938 for London, where he died in 1939. His late works explore culture, religion and the tension between civilization and the drives.",
  "pa.freud.section.concepts": "Key concepts",
  "pa.freud.section.conceptsIntro": "Core ideas that structure Freudian psychoanalytic theory.",
  "pa.freud.concept.unconscious": "The unconscious",
  "pa.freud.concept.unconsciousBody": "Psychic processes outside conscious awareness that influence thought, emotion and behavior. Accessed through dreams, slips, symptoms and free association.",
  "pa.freud.concept.drives": "Drives (Triebe)",
  "pa.freud.concept.drivesBody": "Life drive (Eros) and death drive (Thanatos) as fundamental motivational forces. Sexuality and aggression are reworked through the concept of drive and its vicissitudes.",
  "pa.freud.concept.oedipus": "Oedipus complex",
  "pa.freud.concept.oedipusBody": "Central childhood configuration of desire, rivalry and identification with parental figures. Foundation of character formation and neurotic conflict.",
  "pa.freud.concept.transference": "Transference",
  "pa.freud.concept.transferenceBody": "Revival of past relational patterns in the analytic relationship. The main tool of analytic work — what is repeated can be worked through.",
  "pa.freud.concept.defense": "Defense mechanisms",
  "pa.freud.concept.defenseBody": "Unconscious strategies (repression, projection, displacement, etc.) that protect the ego from anxiety. Symptoms reveal the return of the repressed.",
  "pa.freud.concept.dreams": "Dream work",
  "pa.freud.concept.dreamsBody": "Dreams as the royal road to the unconscious. Condensation, displacement and symbolic representation transform latent thoughts into manifest content.",
  "pa.freud.section.works": "Reference works",
  "pa.freud.section.worksIntro": "Essential texts for studying Freudian psychoanalysis.",
  "pa.freud.work.hysteria": "Studies on Hysteria (1895)",
  "pa.freud.work.hysteriaBody": "With Breuer. Case of Anna O. and the cathartic method. Birth of the talking cure.",
  "pa.freud.work.dreams": "The Interpretation of Dreams (1900)",
  "pa.freud.work.dreamsBody": "Freud's magnum opus. Theory of dream work, wish fulfillment and the method of interpreting dreams.",
  "pa.freud.work.jokes": "Jokes and Their Relation to the Unconscious (1905)",
  "pa.freud.work.jokesBody": "Parallels between jokes, dreams and symptoms. Pleasure and the economy of psychic energy.",
  "pa.freud.work.sexuality": "Three Essays on the Theory of Sexuality (1905)",
  "pa.freud.work.sexualityBody": "Infantile sexuality, perversion, puberty. Foundational for drive theory and psychosexual development.",
  "pa.freud.work.pleasure": "Beyond the Pleasure Principle (1920)",
  "pa.freud.work.pleasureBody": "Repetition compulsion, trauma, death drive. Major theoretical turn in Freud's late work.",
  "pa.freud.work.ego": "The Ego and the Id (1923)",
  "pa.freud.work.egoBody": "Structural model: id, ego, superego. Dynamic relations between psychic instances.",
  "pa.freud.work.civilization": "Civilization and Its Discontents (1930)",
  "pa.freud.work.civilizationBody": "Tension between individual drives and social demands. Culture as source of both protection and suffering.",
  "pa.freud.section.legacy": "Legacy",
  "pa.freud.section.legacyIntro": "Freud's influence on psychoanalysis and culture.",
  "pa.freud.legacy.schools": "Psychoanalytic schools",
  "pa.freud.legacy.schoolsBody": "Freud's work gave rise to diverse traditions — ego psychology, Lacanian, Kleinian, relational and others — all engaging with and revising his original insights.",
  "pa.freud.legacy.technique": "Analytic technique",
  "pa.freud.legacy.techniqueBody": "Free association, neutrality, abstinence, interpretation of transference and resistance remain central, adapted by each school to contemporary practice.",
  "pa.freud.legacy.culture": "Cultural impact",
  "pa.freud.legacy.cultureBody": "Freud transformed how we understand mind, art, religion and society. His concepts entered everyday language and influenced literature, film and the human sciences.",
